Q1 Growth and biomass accumulation

For example, the log transformed data above has a mean of 1.044 and a 95% confidence interval of ±0.344 log-transformed fish. The back-transformed mean would be 101.044=11.1 fish. The upper confidence limit would be 10(1.044+0.344)=24.4 fish, and the lower confidence limit would be 10(1.044-0.344)=5.0 fish

Q2 Traits and Nodule count

Traits

Step done for backtransforming the emmeans

m1_amax_log <- lmer(log(amax) ~ treatment*nfixer + log(init_height) + (1|spcode), data = data_for_models)
m1_gs_log <- lmer(log(gs) ~ treatment*nfixer + log(init_height) + (1|spcode), data = data_for_models)
m1_wue_log <- lmer(log(wue) ~ treatment*nfixer + log(init_height) + (1|spcode), data = data_for_models)
m1_pnue_log <- lmer(log(pnue) ~ treatment*nfixer + log(init_height) + (1|spcode), data = data_for_models)

                        pairwise ~ treatment|nfixer,
                        type = "response",
                        adjust = "tukey")$emmeans) %>% 
    
    clean_names() %>% 
    dplyr::select(-c(df,lower_cl, upper_cl,se)) %>% 
    
    
    group_by(nfixer) %>%
    
    mutate(difference = ((response - first(response))),
           perc_difference =((response - first(response) )/first(response))*100) %>% 
    mutate_if(is.numeric, round, 3)

Q3 Do species modulate their traits in response to the addition of nutrients and/or water to increase biomass accumulation and growth rates?

For answering this question I fitted the following models focusing in the 3 way interaction:

\[response \sim\ treatment:nfixer:trait\ + initialheight\ + (1|spcode) \] I have 4 response variables(rgr, total biomass, above and below ground biomass) and 6 traits thus I fitted 24 models. Also I scaled (z-scores) the traits for being able to compare between parameters of different models.

After this I bootstrap the parameters for getting the Confidence intervals

Model comparisons

three_way_param_bootstrap %>%

    mutate(across(where(is.character), as.factor)) %>% 

ggplot2::ggplot(data = .,
               # Highlight significant terms
               aes(x = terms, y = estimate, color = significance, shape = col_2)) +

            ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 0, colour = gray(1/2), lty = 2) +
            ggplot2::geom_point(size = 6, position = position_dodge(width = .9)) +

            # 95% C.I
            ggplot2::geom_linerange(aes(ymin = lower_bound,ymax = upper_bound),
                                    lwd = 1, position = position_dodge(width = .9)) +

            # 99% C.I
            #geom_linerange(aes(ymin = !!yvar - !!se * interval2,

            ggplot2::theme_bw() +

                           strip.text.x = element_text(size = 25),

                           axis.title.x  = element_text(size= 25),
                           panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
                           panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),

                           panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill= NA,
                                                       size = 1.3)) +
            # Add name
            #labs(title = paste0(response_variable)) +

            # Significance colors
            ggplot2::scale_colour_manual(values = c("gray","black")) +

            ggplot2::xlab("") +
